This French language blog post from Kompozite focuses on explaining the CO2 equivalent (CO2e), a critical unit of measurement for greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions. The article appears to provide an in-depth exploration of why this standardized measurement is important for understanding and comparing different types of greenhouse gases. By converting various greenhouse gases to a common unit based on their global warming potential, CO2e allows for more accurate and comprehensive environmental impact assessments. The piece likely discusses how different gases have varying capacities to trap heat in the atmosphere, and how the CO2 equivalent helps scientists, policymakers, and organizations quantify and compare their environmental footprint over different timescales, from decades to centuries.
